e world bring to light a large body of empirical information available for the first time in Diplomatic Security. This book explores the global contexts and consequences of keeping embassies and their personnel safe. The essays in this volume offer case studies that illustrate the different arrangements in the U.S., China, the United Kingdom, France, Germany, Italy, Turkey, Israel, and Russia. Considering the historical and legal contexts, authors examine how states protect their diplomats abroad, what drives changes in existing protective arrangements, and how such measures affect the safety of diplomats and the institution of diplomacy. Diplomatic Security not only reveals how a wide variety of states handle security needs but also illuminates the broader theoretical and policy implications for the study of diplomacy and security alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aDiplomatic and consular servicexSecurity measures. 0aDiplomatsxProtection. 0aEmbassy buildingsxSecurity measures. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aBenghazi.  aDiplomatic Security.  aEmbassies.  aInviolability.  aPrivate Security.  aState Department.  aTerrorism.  acounterespionage.  ainternational norms.1 aBen Zur, Barak, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBezci, Egemen B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrummer, Klaus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCladi, Lorenzo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCullen, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCusumano, Eugenio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCusumano, Eugenio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEro